{
  "text": "Rituximab is a chimeric anti-CD20 monoclonal antibody that can induce antibody-dependent cell-mediated cytotoxicity, complement-dependent cell killing, and induction of apoptotic cell death, especially in B cells [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . Initially, it was used in hematology for the treatment of malignant lymphoma or leukemia, but it was introduced in kidney transplantation because of its suppressive effect on humoral immunity [CITATION_3] . Indeed, the use of rituximab in the introductory period effectively reduces the rate of cAMR after KT. For example, in ABO compatible KT, the rate of cAMR was 28.9% 2 years after KT, but it only 3.5% in patients undergoing KT from an ABO incompatible donor with a desensitization protocol that included rituximab [CITATION_4] . In another study that suggests the therapeutic effect of rituximab on cAMR, the allograft survival rate after the diagnosis of cAMR was superior in the rituximab treatment group than in the control group [CITATION_5] . All the above findings suggest that rituximab could be a relevant treatment option for cAMR.",
